            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Kevin Fong\u2019s story is woven into the very fabric of San Francisco. A second-generation Chinese-American, he grew up in the quiet, foggy avenues of the Sunset District. His father, an immigrant who ran a small, successful import-export business, preached practicality and stability. Kevin, however, was a dreamer, spending his youth sketching in notebooks and tinkering with early computer graphics programs on the family's bulky desktop. This created a gentle, lifelong tension between his father\u2019s expectations and his own artistic drive.\n\nHis educational journey was a compromise. He earned a B.A. in Communications from UC Davis, a practical choice to appease his family. But the pull of creation was too strong. He enrolled in the California College of the Arts, earning an MFA in Digital Media Arts just as the first dot-com bubble burst. Instead of a swift corporate ascent, he faced a landscape of shuttered startups. This period of uncertainty became a blessing in disguise, forcing him to take on freelance projects\u2014designing interactive menus for ambitious restaurants, creating visuals for underground music events, and consulting for small galleries. He learned to be scrappy, versatile, and to value the intersection of art and public experience over pure tech.\n\nToday, Kevin is the Creative Director for a firm specializing in experiential technology. He lives in a restored Edwardian flat in NOPA with his partner, Elena, a landscape architect. His 3.8-mile commute on the 5-Fulton bus is a daily ritual, a time to observe the city's human tapestry. He leaves his tech-driven work life behind when he steps off the bus, preferring weekend hikes in the Marin Headlands and exploring the Mission\u2019s culinary scene over industry networking events.\n\nAt 45, Kevin has achieved the success his father desired, but on his own terms. He feels a deep connection to the city that shaped him, a place of both immense wealth and grassroots creativity. His future aspiration isn\u2019t a bigger title or a higher salary, but to leverage his skills to create a large-scale, permanent public art installation for the city\u2014a digital sculpture that tells the story of San Francisco's ceaseless, beautiful transformation."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\n**Age 14:** He remembers sitting at the kitchen table in the Sunset, his father silently flipping through his sketchbook. It was filled not with homework, but with detailed drawings of impossible, beautiful towers piercing the fog. His father didn\u2019t scold him, but simply closed the book and said, \u201cThis doesn\u2019t build a house, Kevin.\u201d The quiet disappointment in his voice was worse than anger. It wasn\u2019t a moment that crushed him; it was the moment he decided he would one day prove that imagination could, in fact, build something powerful and real.\n\n2.\n**Age 25:** After the dot-com bust, he landed a freelance gig designing an interactive menu for a tiny Hayes Valley restaurant. Standing in the darkened space, he watched the chef\u2019s face light up as shimmering text and images he\u2019d created were projected onto the wall. It wasn't a billion-dollar startup, but it was tangible. In that moment of shared wonder over food and light, he realized the profound satisfaction of using technology not for scale, but for human connection. It taught him to value the street-level over the skyscraper.\n\n3.\n**Age 38:** Standing with Elena on a windy trail in the Marin Headlands, looking back at the city. The fog had rolled in, swallowing everything but the very top of the Golden Gate Bridge and the Sutro Tower, making them look like islands in a white sea. He felt a deep, grounding peace. He wasn't chasing a tech dream or escaping his father's expectations; he was standing right in the middle, sharing a view with someone who understood landscapes, both natural and emotional. It was a moment of profound success.\n\n4.\n**Last Year:** On his evening commute on the 5-Fulton, the bus lurched to a stop on McAllister. He looked out the window and saw his own reflection superimposed over a new glass condo, which in turn reflected a weathered brick apartment building across the street. For a fleeting second, his face, the hyper-modern, and the historic were a single, layered image. It was an overwhelming feeling of being a part of the city\u2019s constant, chaotic, and beautiful collision of timelines. This daily ritual became his most important research.\n\n5.\n**A Few Months Ago:** After a successful client presentation downtown, he walked through an empty, windswept plaza. He stopped, suddenly seeing not concrete, but a canvas. The vision hit him with absolute clarity: a digital sculpture of light, flowing across the ground, its patterns shifting with the movement of people, the sound of a distant foghorn, the rumble of Muni. It was the culmination of everything\u2014his father\u2019s pragmatism, his own art, his life observing the city. He finally saw exactly what he needed to build."
